procstep.procdesc:
The NOAA Navigational Chart 16082, "Pt. Barrow and Vicinity" was used. This chart was previously brought into GIS and refined on the BASC CD. Specifically, we are starting with "noaa16082.tif" and "noaa16082.tfw" from the /BASC folder on the Revision 1 BASC Data CD (RDI, Oct. 2000).
What follows is from the "RDI_BASC_Readme.doc" file on the CD, describing the modifications RDI made to the original scan of the chart.
\BASC
BASC: This directory contains the NOAA Chart 16082 and a number of infrastructure items like roads, fences, etc. The infrastructure was hand drawn on a mylar overlaid on the paper NOAA Chart by Dave Ramey and Richard Glenn. This information was then scanned and vectorized. Some of this infrastructure exists in other directories on this CDROM. The data in this directory was created to fit the NOAA chart in order to make a base map to provide researchers who come to barrow.
Noaa16082.tif This original file did not line up with known georeferenced data. After further testing it was discovered that when the photo was registered to a lat/long grid it still did not line-up. It is suspected the hardcopy NOAA chart has one or more of its features displayed incorrectly, possible the lat/long grid or the hydrography. The image was moved to line up with existing coastline and USGS dlg data. Several different attempts were made to correlate the image. The final result being the most accurate, lining up with most of the other features. Unfortunately it is still not exact which is common when overlaying data from several different sources.
RDI moved the photo by lining it up with established georeferenced data.
Note that elsewhere in this metadata document it says that all of the files are in UTM zone 4, NAD27. The paper chart itself is NAD83. So, when they originally georectified the scan, they must have corrected to NAD27. This indirect way of changing datums might be the reason why they say it doesn't match up perfectly.
The (new, RDI-modified) noaa16082.tif was checked against other coverages and grids that seem to be ok (b43_dem, b43_drg63, and files derived therefrom). It looks really just fine. So, the .tif was used as is for digitizing.
The scanned image from RDI was brought into arcmap. A new coverage was created in arccatalog. The coverage was overlaid on the image and the coastline was digitized using on-screen digitizing inside of arcgis. A mouse was used for cursor input. The digitizer (Evan) zoomed in closely when digitizing.
The original digitized version of this dataset was digitized into UTM, zone 4, NAD83. The data was then projected into UTM, zone 4, WGS84.

attracc.attraccr: Screen digitized, so accuracy is as good as the chart, the screen resolution and scan resolution. Accuracy of the chart is stated as follows: This chart has been corrected from the Notice to Mariners published weekly by the Defense Mapping Agency Hydrographic/Topographic Center and the Local Notice to Mariners issued periodically by each U.S. Coast Guard district to the date shown in the lowere left hand corner (July 28, 1990).
